  "prompt": "Can a set be both a subset and a proper subset?",
  "response": "No, a set cannot simultaneously be both a subset and a proper subset of another set. \n\n- A **subset** \\(A\\) of a set \\(B\\) means that every element of \\(A\\) is also an element of \\(B\\). Formally, \\(A \\subseteq B\\).\n- A **proper subset** \\(A\\) of a set \\(B\\) means that \\(A\\) is a subset of \\(B\\) and \\(A\\) is not equal to \\(B\\). Formally, \\(A \\subset B\\) or \\(A \\subseteq B\\) and \\(A \\neq B\\).\n\nIf \\(A\\) is a proper subset of \\(B\\), \\(A\\) is necessarily a subset of \\(B\\) as well (every proper subset is automatically a subset). However, if \\(A \\subseteq B\\) and \\(A = B\\), then \\(A\\) is a subset but not a proper subset. Therefore, the distinction lies in whether \\(A\\) and \\(B\\) are equal or not.",
